[3] UK (Lancashire)
Date: Tue 16 Jun 2013
Source: Lancashire Evening Post [edited]
http://www.lep.co.uk/news/health/local/measles-case-rise-sparks-warning-1-5857095


Parents are being urged to make sure their children are immunised against measles, as the latest figures reveal that the number of confirmed cases in Lancashire so far this year [2013] have exceeded the total number of cases during the whole of 2012. Since January this year, health chiefs have had more than 350 notifications of measles and up until the end of June, there were 96 confirmed cases. This is higher than the 92 cases that affected people in Lancashire during the whole of last year [2012].

Lancashire County Council has launched a new campaign to make parents aware that one in 10 children are at risk of measles because they are not fully immunised. Aimed at parents of children aged between 10 and 16, and the children themselves, the campaign is aiming to ensure children who missed out on the full, 2-dose MMR vaccine get the full protection of immunisation now.

County Coun Azhar Ali, cabinet member for health and wellbeing, said: "Measles is a highly infectious disease that can be very serious, leading to ear infections, fits, brain damage and even death. "Since January this year [2013], there have been more than 350 notifications of measles in Lancashire, with children aged 10 to 16 most affected. Through this campaign we are urging parents and children to make sure they get the full benefits of vaccination by visiting their local GP. "If people can't remember how many doses they have had, their GP will have a record. Don't take any risks with your child's health -- get them vaccinated now." Through the campaign, information will be sent to all parents of secondary school pupils and primary school pupils in years 5 and 6.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
