[5] Pakistan (Islamabad)
Date: Wed 17 Jul 2013
Source: The Nation [edited]
http://www.nation.com.pk/pakistan-news-newspaper-daily-english-online/islamabad/17-Jul-2013/pims-stung-by-882-measles-cases


As many as 882 cases of measles were reported in Pakistan Institute of Medical Sciences (Pims) during the first 6 months of this year [2013] and the number is going to increase, according to health experts, as no proper catch-up activity was conducted to target the children who missed routine immunisation. Besides, the door-to-door vaccination campaign to combat the disease has also been delayed. The hospital reported 128 admissions to the hospital and confirmed 6 deaths till June [2013]. The data shows that over 50 per cent of patients had been vaccinated against the disease [but] still they contracted the disease while many reported cases were unvaccinated.

The hospital recorded the cases from areas of Islamabad city, Bara Kahu, Alipur, Bari Imam, Rawalpindi, Azad Jammu and Kashmir, Murree, upper Punjab, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa and Gilgit-Baltistan. The majority of the cases are reported from slums and rural areas where coverage of routine immunisation is low, according to the officials of the Expanded Programme on Immunisation (EPI).

According to health officials, Pakistan is a measles endemic country [since] immunity levels in children and routine immunisation levels are also very low, so catch-up activity to vaccinate the default children who missed the routine immunisation and door-to-door campaign is crucial. Initially, the Capital [Islamabad] administration was in denial and was not ready to accept that there was an outbreak of the disease, but after accepting it too late, they failed to take any proper measures to combat the disease, [according to] health experts.

Health experts and officials of the capital administration at a meeting on 8 Jan 2013 had decided to vaccinate children up to the age of 15 years in Islamabad's small communities where measles cases were being reported. But due to weak health infrastructure there has been no micro-plan or massive campaigns to vaccinate the children against the disease. According to officials, nearly 30 per cent of children missed immunisation as health units of Capital Administration Development (CDA) and Islamabad Capital Territory (ICT) lack staff and infrastructure to carry out the campaigns. The population of the capital has increased from 300 000 to about 1.5 million but the number of staff and resources are still the same as they were before when the city was established. And the successive CDA chairmen and the Islamabad commissioners did not plan to invest in the health sector and other areas that directly affect health of the public.

Update: 100 measles patients were brought to different hospitals in the province on Tuesday [16 Jul 2013], including 17 in Lahore. So far 22 321 measles cases have been reported from across the province including 5791 in Lahore. So far 189 children have lost lives to measles in the province including 86 in Lahore.

--
