[8] Canada (travel alert)
Date: Wed 17 Jul 2013
Source: CTV News, Edmonton [edited]
http://edmonton.ctvnews.ca/canadians-reminded-to-protect-themselves-from-measles-dozens-of-cases-reported-1.1371019


The Public Health Agency of Canada has issued a health notice, after dozens of cases of measles were reported in 6 provinces. Officials said so far in 2013, nearly 30 cases of measles were identified in Alberta, British Columbia, Ontario, Quebec, New Brunswick and Prince Edward Island. The number is high, considering at this point in 2012, 6 cases had been reported.

Public Health Canada said measles can cause blindness, encephalitis (inflammation of the brain), or serious respiratory infections, like pneumonia. The illness can also spread easily through contact with a person infected with measles. In addition measles can affect all age groups, and can be prevented by vaccine -- completed in 2 doses. According to health officials, most cases reported so far in 2013 are related to travel so anyone planning to travel to countries where the illness is still common is urged to get both vaccination doses before travelling. While travel restrictions are not in place, travel health notices have been issued for a number of areas in Africa, Asia, Europe, and South America -- more information on the notice can be found online [at http://www.phac-aspc.gc.ca/tmp-pmv/notices-avis/notices-avis-eng.php?id=98].

Anyone who has travelled to the affected areas and develops the following symptoms: fever, runny nose, drowsiness, irritability, red eyes and/or sensitivity to light, small white spots on the inside of the mouth and throat, or a red blotchy rash that starts on the face 3 to 7 days after the start of symptoms, and then spreads to the rest of the body. Symptoms are treated with medication, as there is no specific treatment for measles, and most people who contract it fully recover.

[Byline: Julia Parish]

